12,http://www.armslist.com/posts/1598012,For Sale/Trade:  308 Enfield Jungle Carbine,"Duluth, Minnesota, United States",$ 400,"Listed On: Friday, May 10, 2013",Rifles,no type,308/7.62 NATO                                                                                ,Bolt Action                                                                                ,Rifle,"Ishapore 2a1 No. 1 MkIII. Enfield 7.62x51mm, will fire .308Win no problem, I believe this was cut down from full length size to resemble an original Jungle carbine. Not sure of barrel length, but assuming 18.8 like original jungle carbine. Also has same muzzle break.
Original rear sight removed, Williams adjustable rear peep sight for full length sight radius. I added a rubber butt pad for length, but can be removed.
Spring-loaded bolt, like SMLE, very fast and smooth operating.
All matching Serial #'s. Made in 1968. Finish mostly removed from bolt, looks stainless.
Has a removable 10 round magazine, also can feed M1a stripper clips.
Finish on the gun is outstanding for it's age, wood is good as well, not all dinged up.
Very bright/clean bore and barrel.
Only thing missing from the gun is the front top handguard. I never saw a need to replace it but if you want one, they are very available and cheap.
Ishapore's are not cheap copy's, they were made for the Indian military to stand alongside their FAL's in the same caliber.
There are only 1 of these currently on Gunbroker, and the bidding started at 450, and that's without a rear peep sight.
Can send pics via email, but I'm going on a trip until Monday night so can't sell the gun until then. Thanks for looking."

21,http://www.armslist.com/posts/1598021,For Sale:  A little gun buying help for you guys and gals.,"Raeford, Fayetteville, North Carolina",FREE,"Listed On: Friday, May 10, 2013",Services,no type,no type,no type,no type,"GunBroker is a great place to get a gun you can't find. However GunBroker is no longer a site where you consistently find good deals. (Don’t get upset I said consistently not ever.) I have had several customers buy from GunBroker and come to me for the transfer. They proceed to tell me they got a great deal and even got 10-15% off because they where military or the dealer told them they were special. Then they tell me how much they paid and it is $100-$150 or more than I would have charged them out the door. Don't get me wrong, many guns are now hard to find but they are available. If you can't find a gun locally and really want it, spend whatever it takes. I’m not saying don’t use GunBroker or any of the other gun site as I use them also, but if you want a firearm at least give me a call and ask what price I can do on the Item.  I’m a small dealer but I won’t make people pay panic prices. I use all the same distributors that every gun store in America uses to buy guns wholesale. Most guns arrive within 2 days of the order.  I may not always have the lowest price but I will try. I might even refer you to one of the other shops in town. Thanks and good luck.
Robert
Raeford Guns."

86,http://www.armslist.com/posts/1598086,For Sale:  Yugoslavian SKS,"Glendale, Phoenix, Arizona",$ 300,"Listed On: Friday, May 10, 2013",Rifles,no type,7.62x39                                                                                ,Semi-automatic                                                                                ,Rifle,"Yugoslavia SKS M59/66A1  manufactured by the Zastava Ordnance /Red Banner Works from 1967 to 1970.

The M59 is practically a carbon copy of the Russian SKS and, , was made at Red Banner from 1960-67. The 59/66 series was manufactured at Red Banner from 1967-70. Many M59s were converted to the 59/66 configuration during that time. Most of the 59s and 59/66s had beechwood stocks. Some Yugoslav 59s and 59/66s with teakwood stocks were made for export to Africa.

The main difference between other SKS rifles and the Yugoslav versions is that the bores of the Yugo versions were not chrome plated--Yugoslavia has no significant native chromium ore deposits, chromium was expensive to purchase and Yugoslavia's  relationship with the USSR (a major chromium ore exporter) since 1948 was lukewarm at best. One reason Yugo SKS rifles (in fact all Yugoslav small arms seem ""beefier"") is because Yugoslav cartridges are much ""hotter"" loads than other similar ""East Bloc"" ammo, plus since Yugoslavia's manufacturing capacity was relatively limited, each weapon had to be more durable."
